Flight Activity¶

by Chris Sharkey¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

I pulled two months of flight activity data from the US Bureau of Transportation Statistics. The first month is from September 2001 and the second month is from March of 2020. My reason for focusing on these two months is they were both periods of great upheaval in the airline industry, and I was curious about similarities and differences between the two periods. Since there can are large numbers of flights in the US every month, I kept my data selection to just these two months rather than expanding out to other months.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 29 columns with 1,128,927 rows of data!

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm interested in exploring the number of flights over the course of each month. Additionally, I want to see how cancellations, delays, and diversions were impacted due to the September 11th attacks and the COVID-19 pandemic

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

To explore these features of interest, I'll take a look at number of flights during each day of the month, I'll explore the delay times as well as the delayed 15 minutes boolean field, and even get into the diverted boolean as well.

Univariate Exploration¶

Let's start by looking at the number of flights (number of records) by day of the month. This is going to be a lot of data, so it will be pretty wide.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations? Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

To recap what we just did: we cleaned the data by changing several data types (arrived by 15 minutes late, cancelled, and diverted) and filling in null values for the arrived by 15 minutes late boolean column. Several interesting points to note:

  • We explored the data by day of the month, and even split this into two separate plots: one for September 2001 and one for March 2020.
  • Most flights were not cancelled, and most did not arrive later than 15 minutes.
  • We explored the distribution of several of our numeric variables using histograms. Departure delay, arrival delay, actual elapsed time, air time, and distance were all right-skewed, unimodal distributions.
  • We looked at the number of flights per carrier and found the top carriers by number of flights.
  • We looked at the top destination airports and top destination cities. These were not the same because a city could have multiple airports.

Bivariate Exploration¶

Let's start by looking at flight cancellations by day of the month in September 2001.

In [95]:
plt.figure(figsize=[10,8]) #Make the figure larger
sb.countplot(data=flights_01, x='DAY_OF_MONTH', hue='CANCELLED');

Oh! So while the number of flights that were scheduled were relatively unchanged throughout the course of the month, there was a huge spike in the number of cancelled flights on and after September 11th. This is more in line with what I would have expected to see. What about March 2020? Did we see a similar spike in cancellations?

In [96]:
plt.figure(figsize=[10,8]) #Make the figure larger
sb.countplot(data=flights_20, x='DAY_OF_MONTH', hue='CANCELLED');

Interesting. So this is quite a bit different than the impact that September 11th had on the airline industry. 9/11 caused a huge spike in cancellations. COVID-19, however, gradually caused more and more flights to be cancelled, starting March 17th and then growing through the end of the month. What about the arrival delayed by more than 15 minutes flag? What does that look like over the course of the month of September 2001?

In [98]:

The only interesting data points here would be September 11th and September 12th. With very few flights occurring on those days, many flights were cancelled and very few had arrival delays greater than 15 minutes. What about March 2020?

In [99]:
plt.figure(figsize=[10,8]) #Make the figure larger
sb.countplot(data=flights_20, x='DAY_OF_MONTH', hue='ARR_DEL15');

There's a small downward trend from March 20th to the end of the month in the number of flights with arrival delays of greater than 15 minutes.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

In this section, we saw how 9/11 had a strong impact on the number of cancellations on September 11-13, 2001. COVID-19 impacted the number of cancelled flights more gradually, with cancellations exceeding the number of flights by the end of March. There wasn't much interesting information in the relationships between depature delay, arrival delay, actual elapsed time, air time, or distance.

When we filtered down the data to focus on just the week of September 9-15, 2001, we could see that the departure delays and actual elapsed time were both impacted. For March 2020, the average flight time (average of the actual elapsed time) did decrease during the second half of the month.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

When we plotted the distribution of departure delays, arrival delays, actual elapsed time, and distance against the three top airports (ORD, ATL, and DFW), we noticed once again that the data was quite skewed to the right. The same was true when plotting arrival delays for the four major carriers (Southwest, Delta, American, and United).

Multivariate Exploration¶

Now we get to the good part. How did the major events in September 2001 and March 2020 impact our three major airports and four major carriers? Let's explore, starting with the week of the 9/11 attacks.

What about the four major carriers? Were they impacted?

Chicago O'Hare had a much higher rate of departure delays than the other two airports on the 13th, but it was able to bring those delays down to below that of the other two on the 14th and 15th.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

For the week of September 11th, there were significant disruptions to the carriers' and airports' operations. Departure delays increased significantly for both carriers and for the top three airports. For the month of March 2020, the decrease in flight times was much more subtle when I split out by the top four carriers.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

I was surprised by how much of an impact there was on average departure delays during the week of September 11th. You can see just how flat the distribution is when split out by origin airport. I was also surprised that ATL had an increase in average flight times during the later part of the month of March.
